es from my computer diary -- tWhich tells you how to cure a common cold with roasted salt and potato steam and how to remove stains on your red Pioneer tie -- tIn which the detective misbehaves in the movie theater while watching a film with Gerard Depardieu -- tIn which we finally meet Nina’s last lover Lionel, learn of his desire to become a great American writer and read his sketch about Russian roulette -- tWhich tells you what to do when you run into your lover’s wife in the supermarket -- tIn which we learn how Ninotchka was conceived and what made Greta Garbo laugh -- tIn which a mysterious character from the third row packs his bags and makes a confession -- tUp in the air -- tIn which we travel to Russia and watch a musical dedicated to the Soviet Constitution -- tIn which my beautiful grandmother takes her last stroll in Paris -- tIn which I invite you to come home with me but Tram No. 30 runs very slowly -- tIn which I bury my grandmother -- tWhich offers you seven elephants of happiness -- tIn which we dispel our sad thoughts and learn what Ninel Markovna really did in Paris -- tIn which you meet my English professor and drink the cheap wine of our youth -- tIn which we taste a fruit drink and cabbage pirogi at my Alma Mater and learn what happened to Boris Krestovsky in Russia -- tIn which we stop making Eurasian jokes and explore the double life of Yuri Poltavsky-Rizhsky -- tIn which you follow me to Moscow and have a pickle treat -- tIn which we eavesdrop on Comrade Kaganovich -- tIn which we watch The Lilac Sunset and listen to Kachalsky’s songs -- tIn which I meet Cossacks and have a romantic escapade at the Pizza Hut -- tIn which the murderer makes a scene -- tIn which we get homesick in Gorky Park -- tIn which we leave Russia and bid farewell to Rabinovich and Anka the machine gunner -- tWhich tells you that there is no place like home -- tGreta Garbo’s Last Smile -- tPostscript0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA playful literary mystery set in the 1930s and 1990s, Ninochka tells the double tale of two women exiles who are both homesick and sick of home. Tanya, a Russian immigrant living in New York, travels to Paris in an attempt to reconstruct the secret life of Nina B., who was murdered there almost sixty years ago, on the eve of World War II. The murder was never solved, and in an attempt to crack the case, Tanya takes possession of Nina's handbag, which contains her diaries, love letters, kits for embroidering Russian blouses, a mysterious treatise on Eurasian supremacy, and a review of Ninotchka, the film in which Greta Garbo played a KGB agent who finds romance in Paris.Among the potential murder suspects are a charismatic professor and nationalist leader, an aspiring American songwriter, an aging Trotskyite, a Hungarian con artist, a heavy-drinking singer of nostalgic romance, and an athletic Comrade X of unknown origins who was rumored to have returned to the Soviet Union. As Tanya is drawn into this immigrant underworld of displaced people, double agents, and dreamers, she finds herself more and more implicated in the life of the murdered woman. Ultimately, she is forced to return to her native country, where she confronts her own homesickness in the changing post-Soviet world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAmericanszFrancevFiction. 0aAmericanszRussia (Federation)vFiction. 0aConspiraciesvFiction. 0aRussian AmericansvFiction. 0aRussianszFrancevFiction. 0aWomen detectiveszFrancevFiction. 0aWomen immigrantsvFiction. 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.